tspan.tspan: At this point in the election, some Americans might be
wondering whether they’ve been staggeringly wrong
about what our two major political parties stand for.
Hillary Clinton has been calling for both progressive and centrist policies, and
Donald Trump has been calling for, well, unadulterated nationalism. Aren’t
Democrats and Republicans firmly entrenched in their ideologies? Aren’t we
doomed to stare hopelessly across the great chasm of the political center?
We may still be
doomed, but it turns
out that our parties
have a tendency to go
through… phases.
These phases can change the parties to the
point that they become barely recognizable.
You could imagine, for example, today’s
Republican politicians accusing the first
Republicans of being pawns of Big
Government.
And not just when it comes to trampling on “states’ rights.”
Lincoln and his allies pushed for the federal government to
actively meddle in the economy. They wanted to modernize
the country, so they raised tariffs and supported construction
of the railroads. Democrats at that time were concentrated in
the South and, following in the steps of Jefferson, wanted the
government to stay out of their affairs (read: slavery, white
supremacy, Jim Crow laws). Seems backwards, doesn’t it?
The policies of modernization worked well over the three decades following
the Civil War. Too well, in fact. Many monopolistic companies, or trusts,
began to dominate the economy. This trend ushered in the Progressive Era
and its associated trust-busting and consumer protection laws. You might
assume that the Democratic Party spearheaded this progressivism, but you
would be wrong.
New Deal Democrats controlled politics for
many decades, but that control came to an end
in the mid-1960s. You see, the Democratic
Party began supporting the Civil Rights
Movement, and for some reason the white
Southerners in the Democratic base didn’t like
that very much. What did they do? They left
and found a new home in the Republican Party.
Historians call this a
realignment, and it’s
a reminder that the
kinds of people that
make up a political
party can, and often
do, shift around.
These realignments tend to happen
every 30 to 40 years
. A
recent example was the growth of a national conservative
movement led by Nixon and Reagan. After absorbing
Southern conservatives throughout the 1960s and 70s, the
Republican Party concentrated itself firmly around the
political right. Many moderate and liberal Republicans
jumped ship and switched parties in response, resulting in
the very polarized political system we have today.
So our parties have gone from ideologically diverse to homogeneous. They’ve
gone from being close to each other on the political spectrum to staking out
opposing ends of it. They’ve traded key groups of their constituencies back
and forth. What then has stayed consistent in each party’s identity?
Or maybe our society is just moving along the arc of history and our parties
have to periodically adjust. You can make up your own mind on that. Whatever
the reason, our parties are much more malleable than we imagine them being.
The Great Depression saw the end of the
Progressive Era and the rise of Franklin D.
Roosevelt and his New Deal. FDR was a
Democrat, and his policies did align with
the kinds of government intervention
associated with today’s Democrats.
But you might not know that the New
Deal Coalition consisted of not just
liberals but some conservatives as well —
mostly poor white Southerners. Even
weirder is that the Republicans at that
time also had a liberal contingent: the
“progressive conservatives,” embodied
by Eisenhower.
Democrats were indeed
progressive, but the
Republican Party, heavily
influenced by Teddy
Roosevelt, stayed in power
nearly the entire era and
enacted most of the
progressive reforms.
One theory says that the parties
represent two different ways to
prioritize our shared American
values. These priorities manifest
in different policies and stances
based on what America’s current
social and economic realities are.
